@node whatdoes "What does it do"

  This  program  makes work with XPK, PowerPacker or CrunchMania datafiles
  and  executable files crunched with XPK or PowerPacker in PPLoadSeg mode
  much  easier.  This  is  the  successor  to PowerPacker Patcher (PP) and
  Run-time  Data-Decruncher  (RTDD)  by  Michael  Berg  and Thomas Schwarz
  respectively.

  After  installing  the  program, system will see files crunched with the
  above-mentioned crunchers as if they were normal files.

  So from now, loading XPK, PowerPacker or CrunchMania datafiles into your
  favourite  program  (text  editor, graphic program, etc.) which does not
  recognize these files itself, does not make troubles.
@endnode

@node requirements "Program requirements"
@next starting

  This program does not have too excessive requirements:

  It works correctly under any OS version, beginning from 1.3!
  Yes, of course it works under OS 1.3!!!

  Besides, it works with any processor of Motorola 680xx and it also works
  with 0.5 MB RAM (but I recommend at least 1 MB).

  XPKPatch also requires reqtools.library V38+ and @{"xfdmaster.library" link xfdmaster} V38+.
@endnode

@node xfdmaster "The XFDMaster Library"
@next xfdmaster
@prev xfdmaster

  The  xfdmaster.library  offers  much  better  routines  for  recognizing
  crunched  files  than  xpkmaster.library.  Thanks to taking advantage of
  xfdmaster.library,  XPKPatch  can also decrunch encrypted files crunched
  with PowerPacker and executable files crunched in PPLoadSeg mode.

  IMPORTANT NOTE:

  To   decrunch   files   crunched   with   XPK,  xfdmaster.library  needs
  xpkmaster.library  as well. And of course, in spite of this, appropriate
  sub-libraries in LIBS:Compressors are also required.
@endnode

@node starting "Starting the program"
@prev requirements

  This  program  can  be  run  in  the same way as almost every program on
  Amiga, that is: from Shell or from Workbench.

  In  both  cases you can supply XPKPatch with some arguments (in argument
  line when starting from Shell and in ToolTypes when from Workbench).

  Syntax: XPKPatch [-<options>] [<temppath>]
  <temppath> : path for temporary files to be stored
               (default path is 'RAM:')
  <options>  : -c check for viruses (default)
               -n do not check for viruses
               -u unpack executable files
               -s skip executable files (default)
               -m unpack CrunchMania datafiles
               -p skip CrunchMania datafiles (default)

  Because XPKPatch (like PowerPacker Patcher) has a simple virus-detection
  mechanism  (see  @{"Virus  detection" link viruses}),  I  think  it  was  good  to add the
  possibility to turn it on or off.

  Using  the parameters '-c' or '-n' you can turn this function on or off.
  Supplying  XPKPatch  with  '-c' (CHECK) you can turn this option on, and
  supplying it with '-n' (NOCHECK) you can turn it off.

  XPKPatch  also  decrunches  executable  files. However, this function is
  sometimes  unnecessary. So I have added the possibility to turn it on or
  off.

  Using  the parameters '-u' or '-s' you can turn this function on or off.
  Supplying  XPKPatch  with  '-u' (UNPACKEXE) you can turn this option on,
  and supplying it with '-s' (SKIPEXE) you can turn it off.

  NOTE: Do not pack executable files that contain 'Overlay' section. These
  files  remain  still  open after having been loaded, and XPKPatch cannot
  delete a temporary file that stems from such a file.

  XPKPatch  also  decrunches CrunchMania datafiles. This function can also
  be turned on or off.

  Using  the  parameters  '-m' or '-p' you can turn this option on or off.
  Supplying  XPKPatch  with  '-m' (UNPACKCRM) you can turn this option on,
  and supplying it with '-p' (SKIPCRM) you can turn it off.

  All  parameters  are  case  insensitive  and they can either be supplied
  separately or can be linked (eg. '-num'). The sequence of the parameters
  is not important, eg:

  XPKPatch -n -u <temppath>, XPKPatch -nuM <temppath>,
  XPKPatch <temppath> -U -n -m, XPKPatch -u <temppath> -N, etc.

  The other argument is the name of the path where you would like XPKPatch
  to save temporary files (see @{"How does it work" link details 12}).

  If  the  user skips one of the parameters, then its default setting will
  be  chosen.  If  you  do  not  supply  any  parameters, then the default
  settings  will  be chosen, i.e. '-c' (virus detection), '-s' (executable
  files  will  not be decrunched), '-p' (CrunchMania datafiles will not be
  decrunched), and 'RAM:' will be chosen as the path for temporary files.

  In  case  of starting this program from Workbench, the parameters should
  be supplied as follows:

  In ToolTypes item of its icon you must type:

  VIRCHECK = (YES/NO)  (depends  whether you want to turn virus detection
                       on or off)
  UNPACKEXE = (YES/NO) (as above)
  UNPACKCRM = (YES/NO) (as above)

  If you want to choose directory where the temporary files will be saved,
  follow these steps:

  Select  the XPKPatch icon. Then holding down the Shift key, double-click
  on  the  drawer  of  the directory, where you want temporary files to be
  saved.

  Here  again, if you skip one of the parameters, then its default setting
  will  be  chosen.  Supplying  no  parameters results in choosing default
  settings.

  After the correct start of the program, it will display information that
  it  has  correctly  been  installed.  If  it  was started from Shell, it
  detaches itself.

  From that moment the program stays quietly in memory.

  If any errors occur during its installation, it will inform you about it
  by  displaying  suitable  information  which describes the reason of its
  fault.
@endnode

@node stopping "Stopping the program"

  To leave the program simply run it again.

  It  is  possible  to  happen  that  the program will not be removed from
  memory  when you start it again. The reason of such behaviour may be the
  situation  when  some other program tries to load a packed file, that is
  in  the  progress  of  depacking  by  XPKPatch. For more information see
  chapter @{"How does it work" link details 45}.
@endnode

@node viruses "Virus detection"

  XPKPatch  has  built-in a very simple virus-detection mechanism. Despite
  this, it may be recognized as a virus!

  It  happens  so,  because  it  patches  the  following  vectors  in  the
  dos.library:

       Open(), OpenFromLock() (OS V36+), Close(), Write(), Examine(),
                     LoadSeg(), NewLoadSeg() (OS V36+)

  Anty-virus  programs  usually  check  addresses  of  the  vectors of all
  libraries,  and if any address is suspicious (usually < $F80000) then it
  is  possible  that  system is infected by a virus. So if your anty-virus
  program  has found something in memory, and you have XPKPatch installed,
  it  is  probably  not  a  virus. But you should always check it (e.g. by
  using other anty-virus program).

  XPKPatch  works  similarly  - when any program changes the address of at
  least  one  of  the above functions, you will be warned. A change of the
  vectors does not mean a virus!!! Surely, the reason is a program similar
  to XPKPatch that is also trying to install itself.
@endnode

@node using "'Everyday' use of this program"

  If  you intend to use this program 'everyday', it is recommended to make
  it  start  automatically.  The  best  way to do it is to place a command
  which  starts  XPKPatch in the file S:User-Startup. After the program's
  name you may enter its arguments.
@endnode

@node details "How does it work"

  An average user need not read this chapter - information that is covered
  in  it  is not indispensable to use this program in the correct way, but
  you  have  to  know  a  lot  about  programming  the  Amiga  in order to
  understand it.

  XPKPatch  during  its  installation patches the following vectors in the
  dos.library:

       Open(), OpenFromLock() (OS V36+), Close(), Write(), Examine(),
                     LoadSeg(), NewLoadSeg() (OS V36+)

  @{b}@{fg highlight}Functions Open() and OpenFromLock()@{ub}@{fg text}
  If a program (let's name it a caller) opens a file for reading, XPKPatch
  checks  whether  the  file is crunched and whether it is encrypted. Then
  XPKPatch decrunches the file and saves it to the tempoprary directory as
  a  temporary  file. If the file is encrypted, XPKPatch asks for password
  and  then  attempts  to decrunch the file. If decrunching succeeds, then
  the  caller gets a FileHandle to the temporary file. If a file cannot be
  decrunched,  the  caller gets a FileHandle to the original file, or NULL
  if the user provided an incorrect password.

  @{b}@{fg highlight}Function Close()@{ub}@{fg text}
  When  the  caller  closes  the  temporary  file  (which it thinks is the
  original  file)  XPKPatch  notes that the file has been closed. In fact,
  XPKPatch  will close and delete the temporary file only after 5 seconds,
  because  some  programs  open/close  the same file many times in a short
  time. The delay speeds up reading crunched files by such programs.

  @{b}@{fg highlight}Function Write()@{ub}@{fg text}
  When  the  caller  writes something to the temporary file, XPKPatch will
  remember to save the changes to the original file.

  @{b}@{fg highlight}Function Examine()@{ub}@{fg text}
  If the caller needs the correct file size for packed file, XPKPatch will
  change  the  file size in FileInfoBlock, so that the caller will see the
  correct size of the file, as if it was unpacked.

  @{b}@{fg highlight}Functions LoadSeg() and NewLoadSeg()@{ub}@{fg text}
  XPKPatch decrunches also executable files (programs, libraries, devices,
  fonts,  etc.).  Every executable file that is loaded by one of the above
  functions  will be decrunched to the temporary file, loaded from it, and
  then  the  temporary  file  will  be  deleted.  You  need  no longer use
  PPLoadSeg and xLoadSeg because XPKPatch can replace them.

  XPKPatch  counts  every opened file and it will not be possible to leave
  the program before all of the files are closed.
@endnode

@node history "Program history"

  1.0  - 27-Aug-96 First release.

  1.1  - 5-Jul-97 Second release.
         I have removed one, small bug:
         - XPKPatch  after  removing did not free the previously allocated
           memory. But this occured only when the program was started from
           Workbench.

  1.2  - 28-Jul-97 Third release.
         I have removed another, small bug:
         - XPKPatch  after  removing and restoring vectors did not compute
           the correct checksum of the dos.library.

  1.3  - 22-Aug-97 Fourth release.
         I have removed another bug:
         - The  program creates a temporary file during decrunching files,
           which  is  removed  after  the  operation  finishes. Buf if the
           crunched file could not be decrunched XPKPatch created an empty
           file  which  was not removed. Actually it was not caused by the
           program   itself,  because  a  temporary  file  is  created  by
           xpkmaster.library  and  if  an  error occurs the library should
           remove the file by itself.

  1.4  - 11-Feb-98 Fifth release.
         I have added the possibility to decrunch executable files:
         - At  present  the  program  can  also  decrunch executable files
           (programs,  libraries,  devices, fonts, etc.). It gives you the
           possibility  to  crunch these files and save disk space. It can
           entirely  replace  the  program xLoadSeg, but it cannot replace
           PPLoadSeg   because   structure   of  the  file  crunched  with
           PowerPacker is complicated.

  1.5  - 28-May-98 Sixth release.
         I  have  added  the  option  to  turn on or off the mechanism for
         decrunching executable files:
         - Now  you  can  decide  whether  you want executable files to be
           decrunched or not (see @{"Starting the program" link starting 25}).

  1.6  - 18-Nov-99 Seventh release.
         I have removed one, small bug:
         - If  XPKPatch  could not install itself for some reason, then it
           quited  without  freeing  the  previously allocated memory. But
           this occured only when the program was started from Workbench.

  1.7  - 25-Feb-00 Eighth release.
         I have removed two, quite serious bugs and improved argument line
         parser:
         - If  XPKPatch  was  started  from  Shell, it was not possible to
           supply  it  with two options, because it would report an error.
           It was, therefore, impossible to start it with the options '-n'
           and  '-u',  specifying,  at  the  same  time,  the path for the
           temporary files.
         - Starting  from this version, the Shell parameters can be linked
           together (see @{"Starting the program" link starting}).
         - At  an  attempt  to  load  an  executable  file  that  contains
           'Overlay' section, the system would crash.

  1.7a - 30-May-00. Ninth release.
         I  have removed quite a serious bug in the function that performs
         file opening:
         - If  XPKPatch cannot decrunch a file (eg. the file is encrypted)
           then  the program, which is opening the file, should be enabled
           to  load  this file in a crunched form. In many cases, however,
           this was impossible due to a bug in XPKPatch.

  1.8  - 14-Oct-00. Tenth release.
         I have removed some bugs and added many additional features:
         - Now the program uses @{"xfdmaster.library" link xfdmaster}.
         - Now  the  program  can  also decrunch executable files crunched
           with PowerPacker in PPLoadSeg mode. It can entirely replace the
           program PPLoadSeg.
         - I have added implemented CrunchMania format.
         - Now XPKPatch can also decrunch XPK, PowerPacker and CrunchMania
           encrypted files.
@endnode

@node upgrades "Getting upgrades"

  If you live in Poland and want to get an upgrade, send me:

  1. A diskette.
  2. A self-addressed envelope with a stamp.


  If you do not live in Poland, send me:

  1. A diskette.
  2. 2 USD for postage.

  Easy, isn't it? Please keep this rule - it will make my life easier, and
  you can count on fast reply.

  Alternatively,  you  can order through Internet. It was described in the
  chapter @{"Copyright and spreading" link copyright 18}.

  An unregistered user is entitled to get one free upgrade.

  A registered user is entitled to get unlimited number of free upgrades.

  You  do  not  necessarily need to get upgrades from me. All new versions
  should be available on Aminet in util/pack/XPKPatch*.
@endnode

